When is shortness of breath serious?If shortness of breath is accompanied by other symptoms like pain or discomfort, tightness in the chest, lightheadedness, nausea, or vomiting, it’s important to seek medical attention immediately.You should also talk with a doctor if you have experienced shortness of breath for over 1 month or if other symptoms like persistent coughing or swollen ankles are present, as it could be a sign of a more serious condition.Is my shortness of breath an anxiety attack or Coronavirus?Shortness of breath caused by an anxiety attack typically peaks within a few minutes and may be accompanied by other symptoms, such as nausea, heart palpitations, and sweating.On the other hand, shortness of breath caused by COVID-19 lasts for a longer period of time and may be tied to additional symptoms, including fever, dry cough, chills, muscle pain, and a sore throat.Why do I have shortness of breath and anxiety at night?Many people experience panic or anxiety attacks at night, which can cause shortness of breath and may occur without any obvious triggers. Similar to daytime anxiety attacks, there’s no known cause, but a variety of factors could contribute, including stress and genetics.TakeawayIt’s important to remember that anxiety attacks can’t kill you. You won’t suffocate, won’t stop breathing, and won’t die from an anxiety attack. An anxiety or panic attack won’t turn into a heart attack, either.If you’re worried about your physical health, get checked out. Once you’ve been cleared of any physical reasons for your shortness of breath, hold onto that clean bill of health as a reminder when you’re back in an anxious moment.See a mental health professional for further help and assistance with coping techniques.

Thyroid dysfunction may lead to mental health symptoms like anxiety and brain fog. An overactive thyroid is more likely to cause these symptoms, and management typically involves regulating thyroid hormone levels.The thyroid gland produces hormones involved in important body functions, from your metabolism to cognitive tasks and mood regulation. When your thyroid produces too much or not enough hormones, these body functions may be affected. This, in turn, could lead to many physical and mental symptoms, including anxiety. Thyroid conditions may also cause physical symptoms that could mimic those of anxiety disorders, like shakiness and increased heart rate.Can thyroid dysfunction cause anxiety symptoms?Yes, thyroid dysfunction can manifest with anxiety in some people, among other mental health symptoms. A 2020 study in people with autoimmune diseases found that altered thyroid hormone levels increased their likelihood of experiencing symptoms of anxiety and depression. Common thyroid dysfunctions include hyperthyroidism (an overactive thyroid) and hypothyroidism (an underactive thyroid). Common causes of both of these conditions include autoimmune disorders, like Graves’ disease and Hashimoto thyroiditis, respectively.Anxiety can occur in both hyperthyroidism and hypothyroidism but may be more common in people with an overactive thyroid.Excessive production of thyroid hormones (T3 and T4) also causes physical symptoms that may be mistaken as anxiety, like rapid heart rate, heart palpitations, and irritability. In turn, experiencing these symptoms without warning could also trigger anxiety.A 2023 case study illustrated how hyperthyroidism can be misdiagnosed in some people as generalized anxiety disorder (GAD), hence the importance of checking your thyroid function when anxiety symptoms are present.Graves’ disease, the most common cause of hyperthyroidism, has also been associated with symptoms of depression and anxiety, and research suggests that it may be a bidirectional relationship. In other words, anxiety may be a result of Graves’ disease and also a possible trigger. Symptoms of thyroid-related anxietySymptoms of anxiety may vary from person to person. In general, anxiety may cause both physical and mental symptoms, some of which may overlap with hyperthyroidism symptoms, including:persistent nervousness or restlessnessincreased heart rate or palpitationstremors or shakingdifficulty sleeping (insomnia)irritability changes in moodunintentional weight loss persistent fatigue increased appetite or urges to eat difficulty concentratingThese symptoms may vary in intensity and overlap with other medical conditions, too. Only a healthcare professional can provide you with a diagnosis and recommend next steps.Other symptoms of thyroid dysfunctionBesides anxiety, other symptoms of hyperthyroidism may include: heat intoleranceincreased sweating even at lower temperaturesincreased bowel movementsmuscle weaknessdepressionHypothyroidism may also lead to other symptoms, including:unintended weight gain or difficulty losing weightcold intolerancedry skinhair thinningconstipationdecreased sweatingfatiguemuscle stiffness and achespuffy facedepressionHow to manage thyroid-related anxietyManaging thyroid-related anxiety primarily involves addressing the underlying thyroid condition.Professional help for hypothyroidism and hyperthyroidismA primary physician or endocrinologist can assess your thyroid function through blood tests and physical examinations.For hypothyroidism, treatment typically involves hormone replacement therapy with the synthetic thyroid hormone levothyroxine (Synthroid), which you may need to take for life. A healthcare professional will want to regularly monitor your thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) levels to ensure you’re getting the correct dose.Treatment options for hyperthyroidism may include: antithyroid medications such as methimazole (Tapazole)radioactive iodine therapythyroid surgery depending on the severity and cause of your condition Treating the underlying cause of anxiety, if related to your thyroid, may provide long lasting relief. If you continue experiencing symptoms of anxiety, consider talking with a mental health professional.Coping strategies for anxietyAlong with managing the cause of the anxiety, a few coping strategies can help with anxiety symptoms. These may include:Relaxation techniques: Deep breathing exercises, meditation, and yoga can help reduce anxiety symptoms. Healthy lifestyle: Regular physical activity can boost mood and reduce anxiety while a balanced diet rich in nutrients supports your overall health. Mindfulness practices: Incorporating mindful breathing and eating and grounding exercises can increase your awareness of the present moment and reduce anxiety.Support groups: Joining support groups provides community and shared experiences, which may help you manage your anxiety.Professional help for anxietyIf your anxiety symptoms interfere with your daily life, consider talking with a mental healthcare professional. They may recommend:Talk therapy: Cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT) is the most effective form of psychotherapy for managing anxiety. CBT helps you identify and challenge negative thought patterns, teaching you coping skills to manage anxiety symptoms.Medication: In some cases, a healthcare professional may prescribe anti-anxiety medications to help you manage severe and persistent symptoms.Frequently asked questions
