Here are some frequently asked questions about thyroid and anxiety.How do you tell if you have thyroid dysfunction?Only a healthcare professional can determine if you have thyroid dysfunction. They’ll assess your symptoms, perform a physical exam, and likely order thyroid tests like TSH, T3, and T4. If an autoimmune thyroid condition is suspected, they may also order antibody tests. What are the psychological symptoms of thyroid problems?Thyroid dysfunctions may cause mental health symptoms in some people, including anxiety, restlessness, irritability, insomnia, depression, and cognitive difficulties like trouble concentrating.What does thyroid-related anxiety feel like? Every body is unique, and symptoms of thyroid-related anxiety may manifest in different ways. Possible symptoms may include persistent nervousness or restlessness, difficulty sleeping, shaking without apparent reason, and irritability. These may be accompanied by other thyroid symptoms like aches, unintentional changes in weight and appetite, and heart palpitations.TakeawayAnxiety is a possible symptom of thyroid disease, especially hyperthyroidism. Anxiety can also make thyroid dysfunction worse or trigger it.The treatment for thyroid-related anxiety typically involves treating the underlying thyroid disorder with medications or surgery. Addressing anxiety symptoms separately can also help.
